<TEXT>
diplomats business leaders and celebrities 
dropped all pretense of being jaded and demonstrated their 
excitement friday over nelson mandela who later was the star 
attraction at a celebrity fundraiser 
as the antiapartheid leader strode to the podium in the 
vaulted greencarpeted general assembly hall at the united 
nations several hundred delegates and dignitaries jumped to their 
feet to cheer him 
earlier he charmed about 150 top businesspeople at the world 
trade center where he expressed interest in us companies and 
foundations investing in a postapartheid south africa 
there was a crackling excitement in the audience said 
richard leone chairman of the port authority of new york and new 
jersey ive spent a long time on wall street and you dont 
usually see that in an audience of this type it was quite an 
exciting thing 
after the meeting at the skyscraper in lower manhattan mandela 
still basking in the glow of euphoric crowds in harlem and yankee 
stadium a night earlier told reporters the reception has been 
beyond my wildest dreams 
the un speech came on the third day of mandelas trip to the 
united states and his last full day in new york where he struck 
deep emotional and political chords among the hundreds of thousands 
who turned out to see him 
calling apartheid a crime against humanity mandela said 
the sanctions that have been imposed by the united nations and by 
individual governments should remain in place 
the un general assembly has long been a leader in the battle 
against apartheid south africa a un member was ousted from the 
general assembly in 1974 and was not represented when mandela spoke 
security has been extremely heavy in new york for the visit 
in johannesburg south africa a newspaper reported friday that 
police arrested 11 whites in connection with a rightwing plot to 
assassinate mandela president fw de klerk and others 
authorities confirmed the arrests and said all were later 
released 
the afrikaanslanguage weekly vryeweekblad said that under the 
plan mandela would have been shot at johannesburgs jan smuts 
airport when he returned home july 18 
mandela 71 finished the new york leg of his visit with a pair 
of fundraisers one at the home of movie executive arthur krim 
the second at actor robert de niros film production headquarters 
the friday night parties were expected to generate more than 1 
million for the african national congress 
arriving at de niros party to cheers from the 200 or so 
spectators behind police barricades were denzel washington eddie 
murphy bette midler spike lee robin williams joe piscopo and 
lou diamond phillips among others madonna was among those 
expected to attend but by the time the event started she hadnt 
been spotted by reporters outside the event which was closed to 
the media 
the stars entered the restaurant under a banner reading 
artists united against apartheid 
were with him said little steven van zandt well do 
everything he wants us to do were working for the south african 
people 
mandela left after about an hour to cheers from the hundreds of 
people who waited outside in the rain 
lee reported nelson gave an inspiring speech he stressed 
that we should stay committed to the cultural boycott 
mandelas wife winnie taped an interview with phil donahue 
that was televised in some areas friday and will be broadcast 
elsewhere on monday she reiterated that she would be the first to 
resort to warfare if negotiations with the white rulers of south 
africa break down 
mandela started his day with an early morning walk through a 
park adjacent to mayor david dinkins residence where he is 
staying 
during his thursday stroll mandela a former amateur boxer 
asked a police chief about where tyson lives on friday he met the 
former heavyweight champion before the un ceremonies 
the 6foot4 mandela towered over tyson who measures 5 feet 10 
inches as the two locked in a handshake and chatted for about a 
minute they smiled broadly 
hes a fighter in all aspects tyson said later truly he 
is fighting the greatest fight not only for himself but for all 
human rights 
mandelas tour was being used to cement antiapartheid actions 
as well as raise funds for the anc of which mandela is deputy 
president he was released from a south african jail four months 
ago after serving 27 years for his activities on the ancs behalf 
the new york visit is expected to generate some 15 million 
said suzanne dubose one of the mayors financial advisers who is 
handling fundraising chores here 
the city was still totaling how much of a strain mandelas visit 
would put on its already tight budget police overtime alone was 
expected to cost 2 million but dinkins has said he expects the 
state department to pay that bill 
mandela is scheduled to leave for boston early saturday 
