a candidate who appeared to have won the 
democratic primary for governor by a 32vote margin asked the state 
supreme court on friday to block plans for a second recount of the 
ballots 
candidate ben nelson asked the high court to certify him as his 
partys candidate to challenge republican incumbent kay orr in 
november 
unofficial figures from recounts in the states 93 counties 
showed nelson with a 32vote lead over bill hoppner in the may 15 
primary 
earlier this week the state board of canvassers said there 
should be a further recount of some ballots in 23 counties 
on friday nelsons attorneys asked the high court to take 
jurisdiction from district court and order the state board of 
canvassers to certify that nelson won they argued that the canvass 
board failed to comply with its legal duty and certify the election 
results submitted by the counties 
hoppner was on a fishing trip in wyoming on friday and 
unavailable for comment 
if the sevenmember supreme court agreed to nelsons request it 
would have to meet on or before the close of business monday to 
decide the question 
the first recount was automatic because the contest was so 
close the second partial recount sought by the state canvassing 
board was expected to begin early next week 
