<TEXT>
a plan to boost funding for poor and 
middleincome schools at the expense of the wealthiest schools won 
final approval thursday in the state assembly 
the action came just two weeks after the state supreme court 
ruled the system of school funding discriminated against children 
in poor districts new jerseys system dependent on the property 
tax is among a dozen that have been overturned by courts in recent 
years 
the assembly vote on the proposal by gov jim florio on thursday 
morning followed allnight haggling and debate the assembly also 
approved florios proposal for 28 billion in tax increases 
including income tax hikes for residents who make 35000 a year or 
more and raises in sales oil and tobacco taxes 
the bills are now before florio who is expected to sign them 
next week 
the controversial school funding bill cleared the assembly 
4133 with just enough votes for passage the state senate passed 
the school funding plan and income and sales tax increases about 15 
hours earlier with the bare minimum 21 votes all cast by democrats 
higher income taxes will pump 11 billion more in state aid to 
public schools largely to poor and middleincome districts aid 
will be sharply cut or eliminated to the wealthiest 
the powerful teachers lobby bitterly opposed the school funding 
bill because it requires some wealthy districts to pay for pension 
costs the teachers representatives contend that shifting that cost 
from the state endangers teachers financial security 
the state supreme court found the current school funding system 
unconstitutional ordered that it be changed by the 199192 school 
year as in other states schools in welltodo areas were better 
funded because local governments were able to collect more in 
property taxes 
other states where courts have ordered changes in school funding 
are kentucky kansas wisconsin california connecticut 
washington west virginia wyoming arkansas and montana 
the 30 poorest school districts in the state would receive the 
bulk of the new state aid and about 350 suburban and rural 
districts would also see more state money at the same time aid to 
the 250 wealthiest districts would be reduced or abolished by 1995 
republicans bitterly opposed all the proposals they charged the 
school aid plan will decrease aid and raise property taxes in 
middle class communities they represent 
we dont need to penalize one set of school districts in order 
to benefit another said assemblyman robert littell rsussex 
but democrats said it was time to act before another generation 
of youngsters from poor urban communities is lost they said that 
while some districts will lose aid there will be more state aid 
for 73 percent of new jerseys schoolchildren 
this bill guarantees every child in this state will have a 
quality education said assembly speaker joseph doria dhudson 
florio said he would take the package to the public explaining 
its benefits to propertytax payers and schoolchildren 
this will not be a difficult thing for us to sell he said 
</TEXT>
