<TEXT>
with the citys homicide rate up nearly 60 percent 
during last year officials hope beefedup patrols neighborhood 
youth programs and an antigang task force can stem the violence of 
summer 
but with homicide rates on the rise in big cities like new york 
and dallas no one is quite sure how to reduce the drugrelated 
gunplay and gang warfare on the streets as summer begins 
its troubling said jim jordan spokesman for the boston 
police department which reported 74 homicides so far this year 
compared with 51 from january to july 1 of 1989 
in boston that means steppedup police patrols in highcrime 
areas like roxbury and dorchester and the vigilance of a antigang 
task force that has made 269 arrests of gang members since its 
formation in march 
the citys safe neighborhoods plan targets youth in the 
innercity by offering them hundreds of options to stay off the 
streets 
city officials business and community leaders hope to guarantee 
a summer job to every teenager who wants one they also have 
scheduled hundreds of activities ranging from cookouts to 
neighborhood cleanups 
more important is the citys decision to maintain the program 
yearround said safe neighborhoods director ted landsmark 
violence went up last fall when folks went back to school so 
we learned we have to keep it going all year landsmark said 
we know itll help during the summer and for the rest of the 
year too 
federal drug czar william bennett last week said antidrug 
efforts have caused a shortage of cocaine that could lead to 
violence there will be the same number of dogs fighting over a 
smaller number of bones bennett said 
in texas more than 150 elected dallasarea officials including 
the mayor and chief of police meet friday to map an anticrime 
strategy for the summer 
dallas police business and community leaders also instituted 
project city a program aimed at providing recreation and 
employment for youth in the mostly black and hispanic oak cliff 
area 
historically we see a 10 to 15 percent increase in crime in 
the summer and we like to do something about it beforehand said 
police sgt jim chandler the homicide rate in dallas is up 16 
percent over last year 
chicago has added 50 officers to the police anticrime unit for 
the summer and has beefed up the narcotics unit 
we can deal with the enforcement part but the jails are 
overcrowded and people get out faster said tina vicina a 
chicago police spokeswoman she said the 375 reported homicides in 
chicago is nearly even with last years rate but she said it 
always gets worse in the summer 
in new york where the homicide rate is up 29 percent over last 
year police arent planning anything special for this summer 
its not good said new york police det joseph mcconville 
we need more cops but we got budgetary restraints well just be 
deploying officers where we think theyre needed 
in los angeles where 412 homicides were reported as of june 14 
compared with 386 for the same time last year the police 
department has announced no specific plans for the summer said 
officer don lawrence 
