<DOCNO> AP900622-0012 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
president bushs suspension of talks with 
the plo will strengthen the hand of palestinian militants and 
hardline arab states who oppose yasser arafats peace effort it 
also will intensify growing antiamerican sentiment 
bushs decision wednesday to freeze the 18monthold talks 
rather than break them off completely has left the door open for 
contacts to resume 
but the breakdown raises the prospects of a resumption of 
widescale terrorism at a time when passions in the middle east are 
flaring and moderate leaders are warning that a new arabisraeli 
conflict may be looming 
bush suspended the talks because arafat refused to condemn an 
abortive guerrilla attack on israel 
the lowlevel dialogue began in december 1988 when the united 
states ended a 13year boycott following arafats renunciation of 
terrorism and recognition of israels right to exist it was seen 
as a breakthrough in the tortuous middle east peace process 
but palestinian leaders have become increasingly disillusioned 
with washingtons inability to prod israel into peace talks with 
the palestine liberation organization 
well not shed any tears over the us decision arafats 
top lieutenant salah khalaf said in tunis the dialogue 
produced no positive results 
we recognized israel we did everything the americans asked 
and israel didnt give an inch khalaf said 
the prospect of talking directly to the americans may have 
been the carrot that prompted arafat to renounce terrorism and 
explicitly recognize israel but the dialogue or rather the 
threat to break it off has come to be seen by many palestinians 
and not all of them radicals as a stick brandished by the united 
states to extract ever greater concessions from the plo without 
offering anything in return veteran analyst charles snow wrote 
in the middle east economic survey a few days ago 
the plo leadership has not said what it will do but arafats 
peace initiative looks dead in the water along with the bush 
administrations effort to mediate a peace settlement 
saeed kamel the top plo official in cairo said thursday the 
palestinian leadership is currently considering options to press 
forward toward peace this will be unveiled in the coming weeks 
he refused to elaborate but his statement indicated arafat is 
not about to reverse course and opt for allout violence 
a government official in cairo which has mediated between 
israel and the united states said egypt will support arafat and 
his moderate policy and curb the palestinian militants 
arafat said recently that if his peace effort failed he would 
call a meeting of the palestine national council the palestinians 
parliamentinexile submit his resignation as plo chairman and say 
i am returning your mandate 
kamels statement appeared to indicate this point has not been 
reached 
however it is unlikely that arafat will bow to us demands 
that he discipline mohammad abass maverick leader of the palestine 
liberation front for launching the may 30 attack and dismiss him 
from the plos ruling executive committee 
arafat insists that only the palestine national council can 
dismiss abass from the plos executive committee 
with the dialogue suspended arafat may feel even less inclined 
to punish abass whose small faction is part of the plo if he did 
crack down on abass he risks alienating the plos radicals and 
triggering widespread defections 
there has been no indication so far that arafat will respond to 
the us decision by unleashing his guerrillas against israel again 
but there is always the risk that the militants will take 
matters into their own hands with the dialogue on the rocks they 
no longer believe there is anything to lose 
despite the efforts of leaders like king fahd of saudi arabia 
and president hosni mubarak of egypt moderation is in short supply 
in the arab world these days 
antiamerican feeling is growing because of what many arabs see 
as washingtons political military and economic support for israel 
a longtime moderate figure in jordan former foreign minister 
taher masri said recently the americans are too cowardly to do 
anything 
the state department on thursday urged americans traveling to 
the middle east and elsewhere to exercise extra caution 
the arabs also blame the americans for doing nothing to prevent 
a wave of immigration to israel by soviet jews israeli officials 
expect 150000 by the end of the year and say up to 1 million will 
seek to settle in the jewish state in the next few years 
the arabs fear many will settle in the occupied west bank and 
gaza land proclaimed an independent palestinian state pushing out 
large numbers of palestinians 
the plo is losing support in the occupied zones to the extremist 
islamic fundamentalists of the gazabased hamas group who advocate 
an allout struggle against israel 
arafats credibility in the occupied territories where 
palestinians have been waging an uprising for the last 30 months 
is likely to be eroded further because of his failure to achieve a 
political breakthrough the prospect of that is now more remote 
than ever 
khalaf warned last month that the plo leaders run the risk of 
becoming generals without troops 
arafats critics stress that the uprising has neither persuaded 
the israelis to relinquish the west bank and gaza nor persuaded 
them to consider peace talks with the plo 
in this climate of uncertainty and frustration coupled with a 
buildup of longrange missiles and weapons of mass destruction 
what happens in the next few weeks will be crucial 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
ed blanche is the aps middle east news editor 
and has covered the region since 1985 
</TEXT>
