<TEXT>
seventeen shrimp fishermen have been ordered 
to pay fines up to 12000 for failing to equip their nets with 
devices required under federal rules to protect sea turtles 
it was the first major decision on enforcement of the 
regulations requiring turtle excluder devices or teds 
hugh j dolan an administrative law judge in the department of 
commerce ruled the fishermen must pay the fines despite protests 
that the cagelike devices would cause them financial ruin 
those who conduct commercial fishing operations are obligated 
to know what the law and regulations are and to abide by them 
said dolan ruling from washington 
his ruling signed tuesday and released thursday upheld fines 
proposed by the national oceanic and atmospheric administration 
three of the fishermen were fined 500 but most were fined 7500 
or 8000 the highest fine was 12000 
the shrimpers in the gulf of mexico could have settled out of 
court by installing teds but decided not to officials said most 
of the 17 fishermen are vietnamese immigrants 
the devices allow sea turtles to escape from shrimp nets 
fishermen complain teds let the shrimp escape also 
dolan said tee john mialjevich of new orleans head of concerned 
shrimpers inc who represented the fishermen misled the 17 
he assertedly told the shrimpers they did not have to obey the 
law and that no fines needed to be paid because the law was to be 
changed dolan wrote 
mialjevich would not comment thursday 
federal officials first ordered shrimpers to install teds in 
june 1987 but protests and legal fights delayed their use until 
the commerce secretary put regulations in full force in september 
1989 
joe gibson a spokesman for the coast guard said about 325 
citations for trawling without the devices were issued in 1989 and 
1990 records for this year show 218 of 373 vessels boarded by the 
coast guard had teds he said 
in washington marydele donnelly director of sea turtle 
programs at the center for marine conservation said this will 
go a long way to improving that situation 
in his decision dolan cited a new study on sea turtles by the 
national academy of sciences that recommended teds to save turtles 
the study said shrimp nets kill more turtles than all other human 
activity combined 
i am not unsympathetic to the plight of these hard working 
fishermen dolan said but he added that all gulf shrimp 
fishermen must abide by the laws enacted to protect endangered sea 
turtles 
</TEXT>
