<DOCNO> AP900622-0062 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the changing terminology of aids does more 
than shape the way people talk about the disease experts say it 
shapes everyones way of thinking about and responding to the 
epidemic 
activists at the sixth international conference on aids this 
week are so sensitive to some words and phrases they distributed a 
buzzword flyer it spells out why speakers at the meeting 
which began wednesday and continues today run the risk of being 
booed if they use politically incorrect words 
among the taboo phrases are highrisk groups innocent 
victims and intimate sexual contact 
the evolving terminology of aids is based on the idea that 
language is political said robin lakoff a linguistic professor at 
the university of california at berkeley 
in the last 30 years people have become more sensitive about 
the language they use and about the language used about them she 
said 
disempowered groups will change the language about them to gain 
respect and authority she said the civil rights movement 
effectively changed negro to black and the womens 
movement changed lady to woman for that reason 
aids workers prefer highrisk behavior to highrisk 
groups because actions such as sharing drug needles spread aids 
not mere membership in a group such as intravenous drug users 
language change may start out as a psychological factor for 
empowerment lakoff said but it has very real consequences the 
way you think can change your behavior 
calling an infant an innocent victim of aids is considered 
very impolitic aids workers say because it implies other people 
living with aids somehow deserve it and should feel guilty about 
contracting the disease 
aids workers also say people are not aids victims they are 
people with aids or more recently people living with 
aids to call people victims strips them of dignity workers 
say 
dr david wilkins an associate professor of linguistics at the 
university of california at davis said he has found evidence of a 
skewed terminology prompting ignorance about a subject 
in wordassociation tests using aids as a prompt word 
wilkins said his students responded with such words as death 
gay fear homosexual 
people learn the words wilkins said but they use the 
words to convey these associations not what the words actually 
mean 
aids educators are rankled by terms they find too vague such as 
bodily fluids semen vaginal fluids and blood are known to 
transmit the human immunodeficiency virus hiv but not tears 
sweat and saliva 
similarly intimate sexual contact makes some people think of 
kissing and fondling aids activists say the media should name 
specific acts of sexual intercourse in discussions of highrisk 
behavior 
using specific language instead of polite euphemisms and using 
nonjudgmental language was crucial in this citys attempts to 
treat the disease said rene durazzo of the san francisco aids 
foundation 
one of the reasons we have been able to be successful is that 
we have been able to stress behavior without pointing fingers 
durazzo said if the language seems to be judgmental you start 
to alienate the very people you want to reach 
recently durazzo named one of the most important changes in the 
aids language as being the shift to discussing hiv as a critical 
problem not just aids 
rather than calling hiv the aids virus durazzo prefers that 
aids be portrayed as the most acute stage of infection with hiv 
there was a misconception that people who were infected but 
didnt show it were well durazzo said with the increased focus 
on hiv durazzo said funding and awareness of early intervention 
programs has increased significantly 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

