<TEXT>
the soviet union has begun removing nuclear 
warheads from some of its more volatile republics out of concern 
that the weapons may fall into the hands of nationalist elements 
an administration official said today 
its the prudent thing to do said the official alluding to 
the upheavals that have occurred in the baltic region and in other 
areas in the southeastern part of the country the official asked 
not to be identified 
stephen meyer an expert on the soviet military and a professor 
at the massachusetts institute of technology said soviet 
government officials told him of the consolidation 
there is a consolidation going on he said adding it 
appears the soviets may also be concerned that warheads from a site 
in a rebellious republic could be handed over to iran or another 
third world country 
the wall street journal which reported the story in todays 
editions said the soviets have told american officials and experts 
that they have consolidated control over 33000 nuclear warheads 
the state department had no comment on the report 
the article said one soviet concern is the possibility of a 
breakdown of central authority in the country followed by civil war 
a second concern involves the possible theft of nuclear weapons 
in the event that a soviet storage site were overrun by rebel 
forces it said 
at the soviet embassy in washington spokesman georgi v 
shchekochikhin said he had no information that warheads had been 
moved he referred questions to the soviet foreign ministry 
the journal article said the effort appears to focus on bringing 
tactical nuclear weapons such as shortrange missiles nuclear 
artillery and bombs into the russian republic 
it added that the move is not believed to include longrange 
strategic nuclear weapons and therefore does not constitute a 
change in the superpower balance of forces 
meyer said it seemed from his conversations with soviet 
officials that the consolidation began after violence flared last 
january between armed azerbaijani and armenian groups around the 
city of baku where some nuclear warheads are believed to be 
stored moscow sent russian airborne units to stop the fighting 
but isolated attacks on military units in that area reportedly have 
continued 
meyer said the consolidation involves both nuclear warheads and 
conventional or nonnuclear armaments he equated the move with a 
us decision in the 1970s to sharply reduce the number of nuclear 
warhead storage sites in western europe in response to a rise in 
terrorist threats against us installations 
