<TEXT>
personal spending was flat in may the 
government said friday in a report indicating growing caution among 
consumers who have been a major source of strength for the economy 
during seven years of growth 
the consumer clearly has pulled back in a dramatic fashion 
said stephen s roach senior economist with morgan stanley amp co 
in new york 
the commerce department said consumer spending remained 
unchanged at a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 366 trillion 
after seven straight months of gains including 05 percent in 
april and 03 percent in march 
but even the april and march advances were weaker than first 
thought they were revised downward from 06 percent and 05 
percent reported last month 
consumer spending is considered a barometer of economic health 
since it accounts for about twothirds of the nations economic 
activity 
analysts have cited a poor job market and weak wage increases 
for the flagging consumer confidence 
indeed the commerce department said personal incomes rose just 
03 percent in may for a second straight month to a seasonally 
adjusted annual rate of 470 trillion the identical gains 
followed three consecutive monthly advances of 08 percent and were 
the lowest since a 02 percent increase last september 
the income gains have not even matched the inflation rate 
observed economist sandra shaber of the futures group a washington 
management consulting firm certainly consumers are feeling the 
pinch she said 
fridays report was the latest indicating a slowdown in consumer 
spending which has been a driving force for much of the current 
economic expansion now in its eighth year 
the commerce department reported last week that retail sales 
fell in may their third consecutive monthly decline it was the 
first time retail sales fell for three straight months since the 
summer of 1981 during the last recession retail sales represent 
about half of overall consumer spending 
and the department on thursday revised downward its previous 
estimate of consumer spending in the first quarter 
nevertheless roach said the slow pace of consumer spending is 
not likely to tip the economy into a recession since there are 
other things out there still boosting the economy 
roach cited a second commerce department report friday showing 
that orders for durable goods bigticket items expected to last 
at least three years jumped 39 percent in may 
paul getman an economist with regional financial associates in 
west chester pa said there have been some signs recently of a 
manufacturing rebound 
exports are healthy and inventories are rather low which 
bodes okay for a pickup in manufacturing and durable goods over the 
next six months getman said 
the difference between incomes and spending in may helped 
improve americans savings rate the rate savings as a percent of 
disposable income rose to 62 percent following a 60 percent 
rate in april and a 63 percent rate in march the march rate was 
the highest in five years 
a higher savings rate means less dependence on foreign capital 
since more funds thus would be available domestically for business 
investment 
the report said americans income after taxes increased 02 
percent the same rate as in april the key component of the income 
category wages and salaries rose 103 billion after a 164 
billion gain in april 
on the spending side purchases of durable goods fell 126 
billion after an 85 billion gain in april durable goods 
purchases had fallen the previous two months 
purchases of nondurable goods were down 500 million in may 
their third consecutive decline spending on services slowed to 
131 billion after a 147 billion gain in april and a 196 
billion advance in march 
