<TEXT>
the two germanys for 40 years the 
most visible symbol of the cold war divide on friday took their 
biggest step toward unification by reaching final agreement on 
economic merger 
in east berlin representatives of the world war ii victors and 
vanquished gathered to discuss german unity and one of the most 
notorious markers of eastwest conflict checkpoint charlie was 
removed from the berlin wall 
soviet foreign minister eduard shevardnadze in berlin for the 
unity talks said a united germany could join nato after a 
fiveyear transition period and the pullout of foreign troops from 
the country secretary of state james a baker iii rejected the 
proposal saying it was a decision for the germans to make after 
unification 
nonetheless shevardnadze said later he hoped agreement on 
unification could be reached by the end of the year 
despite international differences over unification the german 
states continued the race to merge 
government officials in bonn speaking on condition of 
anonymity said an allgerman election was most likely dec 9 
they said chancellor helmut kohl preferred that date because it 
would allow a new parliament to convene in early january an 
earlier date would have required the new parliament to meet between 
christmas and new year the sources said 
wighard haerdtl an official in west germanys interior 
ministry said friday negotiations were under way between east and 
west germany for a second treaty outlining the consitutional 
aspects of german unification he said it should be ready for 
signing in september 
the only real remaining obstacle to unification is the military 
stance of a united germany the united states and western allies 
want the new country to be a member of the north atlantic treaty 
organization the soviet union has refused to accept this 
baker rejected shevardnadzes conditional acceptance plan 
friday saying the issue should be decided by a sovereign germany 
with little fanfare the upper house of the west german 
parliament on friday approved the treaty that will merge the 
economies of the german states on july 2 
on that day the powerful west german deutsche mark takes over 
east germanys 40 years of rigid socialism gives way to capitalism 
and the borders that once separated families and worlds will fall 
on thursday lawmakers in the east german parliament and the 
powerful lower house of the west german parliament overwhelmingly 
approved the economic treaty and sealed their decision with joyous 
applause 
both countries also pledged to respect polands western border 
and not make any territorial claims after unification on german 
territory lost after world war ii the issue had become one of the 
most sensitive in the unification realm about a third of 
presentday poland is former german territory 
west german finance minister theo waigel appeared before the 
bundesrat or upper house friday to argue for passage of the 
economic treaty 
the west german opposition social democrats had long criticized 
the swift pace of unification and complained the treaty on 
monetary economic and social union didnt contain enough 
safeguards for east germans as they move from a socialist economy 
to a free market 
nontheless passage had been virtually assured social 
democratic chairman hans jochenvogel had said thursday they 
wouldnt torpedo the treaty because east german expectations were 
too high and uncontrollable events could result from a novote 
in fridays debate lothar spaeth governor of the 
badenwuerttemberg state and a member of kohls christian 
democrats called it a most ridiculous argument that economic 
unification move more slowly 
the people over there have set the pace he said noting the 
hundreds of thousands of east germans who fled their repressive 
communist country last year after borders were open to the west 
kohl was meeting with french president francois mitterrand on 
the rhine when the economic treaty gained final approval and there 
was no immediate reaction from the man who aspires to be the first 
chancellor of a unified germany 
in a plea thursday for approval of the pact he said the hopes 
of the people of germany for the unity and freedom of all germans 
are about to be fulfilite the rush to unification there are many fears 
about next 
months economic merger 
some experts have predicted up to 2 million east germans will 
lose their jobs as outmoded governmentowned factories and 
businesseled 
desps try to compete in the freemarket system more than a 
third of the enterprises are expected to close and social unrest 
could result 
west germans worry how much unification could cost them either 
in possibly higher taxes or inflation 
however the west german government has said it wont raise 
taxes and in may unveiled a nearly 70 billion german unity fund 
to be used to rebuild east germany 
