a hardline critic of mikhail s gorbachev gained 
the most votes friday in the election for a new communist party 
chief in the russian federation and was favored to win the post in 
a runoff 
a victory by ivan polozkov could turn the communist party in the 
russian federation the soviet unions largest republic into a 
power base for conservatives it could also cause a split in the 
national communist party 
the new leader was expected to be named saturday 
polozkov received the most votes among seven nominees friday 
with 1017 to 848 for moderate oleg lobov soviet journalists 
predicted polozkov would win enough of the total 2633 votes from 
the defeated conservatives to triumph in the runoff 
technically all communists are automatically considered members 
of both the national and republic parties but a delegate from the 
volga river city of kuibyshev said the election of the conservative 
polozkov as head of the russian party could cause half the 
communists in his area to quit 
the national communist party congress meets in nine days to 
revamp its program and leadership and many expect it to split 
just three weeks ago radical reformer boris yeltsin was elected 
president of russia that gave gorbachev a strong rival on the 
other side 
it is not known if gorbachev and his centrists would side with 
conservatives with reformers or head out on their own 
but this weeks russian party congress made a gorbachev alliance 
with hardliners seem unlikely they repeatedly attacked the soviet 
presidents reforms and applauded speakers calling for gorbachevs 
replacement as head of the national party 
leaving the party job legally would not affect gorbachevs 
position as president of the soviet union 
the russian communist party was reestablished this week for the 
first time since 1925 at that time it was absorbed into the 
national party partly for fear its leaders could become competitors 
in the struggle for power russia contains half the soviet people 
more than half of its communists and threequarters of its land 
despite polozkovs harsh criticism of reform gorbachev backed 
him three weeks ago for president of the russian republic against 
