<DOCNO> AP900622-0126 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
sir tom hopkinson a pioneer in photojournalism 
who used stark unadorned pictures to raise awareness of societys 
ills has died his family said friday he was 85 
hopkinson died wednesday at oxford where he lived no cause of 
death was given 
hopkinson was editor of the now defunct magazine picture post 
from 1940 to 1950 and was also editor of the south african magazine 
drum from 1958 to 1961 
after earning his masters degree at oxford university he 
worked in advertising and as a freelance journalist he became 
involved in the art of photojournalism in 1934 as assistant editor 
of the magazine weekly illustrated 
picture post was launched in 1938 by publisher edward hulton 
with stefan lorant as editor and hopkinson as his assistant 
hopkinson took over as editor when lorant emigrated to the united 
states in 1940 
hopkinson specialized in bold observant photographs and 
coverage of news and social issues in britain and abroad that 
depicted peoples lives without gloss or gimmickry 
we on pictire post were out to influence events in a 
particular direction that of a more just and equal society 
hopkinson said once in an interview 
picture post photographs such as one by bert hardy of slum kids 
in the scottish city in glasgow in 1948 became classics of 
photojournalism 
hopkinson quit the magazine in 1950 along with reporter james 
cameron when hulton stopped publication of a story cameron brought 
back from the korean war about mistreatment of political prisoners 
by south korea 
in his time at picture post hopkinson schooled a generation of 
young photographers and writers to link pictures and words to 
increase the impact of a story the magazine folded in 1957 
after leaving the magazine hopkinson wrote several books from 
1954 to 1956 he was features editor of the now defunct london 
newspaper the news chronicle and also worked as a journalistic 
adviser to independent televisions current affairs program this 
week 
in 1958 he accepted an invitation by jim bailey the owner of 
drum to go to johannesburg as editor of the magazine which was 
aimed at black readers 
he recalled his experiences with the magazine and his travels in 
africa in his 1962 book in the fiery continent 
he later moved to nairobi kenya where from 1963 to 1966 he was 
regional director of the international press institute and headed 
an ipi center to train black journalists 
in 1967 he became a lecturer in journalism at the university of 
sussex in southern england he was a visiting professor in 
journalism at the university of minnesota from 1968 to 1969 
in 1970 he became director of the center for journalism studies 
at university college in cardiff in wales he was knighted by queen 
elizabeth ii for his services to journalism in 1978 
he is survived by his wife and three daughters 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

