<TEXT>
here are highlights of the treaty that prepares the economic 
merger of the two germanys in july and the separate resolution 
recognizing polands borders 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
overview the two germanys agreed to create a monetary 
economic and social union as a first step to unification under the 
west german constitution the international implications of the 
merger must be resolved in talks among the four victorious world 
war ii powers the soviet union the united states britain and 
france 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
monetary union on july 1 the west german mark becomes the 
legal tender in east germany but because that day is a sunday 
actual implementation will be july 2 the west german bundesbank 
or central bank will have control over monetary policy in both 
countries the economic union will be based on a freemarket 
economy 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
conversion rates workers will have their wages converted from 
east german marks to west german marks at a 11 rate 
for savings deposits east germans 14 and younger will be able 
to convert up to 1200 at a 11 rate those aged 1559 will be 
able to convert 2400 at the 11 rate people 60 and older can 
covert up 3600 at the favorable rate all other savings will be 
converted at two east marks for one west mark 
east german pensions will be brought to west german levels 
raising most of them 
debts will be converted at a 21 rate more favorable to 
troubled east german companies 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
border resolution in a separate resolution the parliaments of 
east and west germany recognized polands western border 
delineated by the oderneisse rivers the resolution said both 
sides declare that they will not raise territorial claims now or in 
the future 
the resolution was necessary to generate international support 
or the rapidly approaching unification about onethird of present 
day poland is former german territory lost after world war ii 
poles feared a united germany might try to reclaim the land a wish 
of many ultraconservative german voters who considered it rightful 
german property 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

