<TEXT>
the soviet union said friday that a united 
germany would have the right to eventually join nato but only after 
a fiveyear transition period during which all soviet and us 
troops would leave the country 
the united states supported by the western allies rejected the 
plan as a delaying tactic 
foreign minister eduard a shevardnadze made the proposal during 
unification talks involving the four world war ii allies and the 
two german states 
shevardnadze also proposed pulling us soviet british and 
french troops out of berlin within six months of a german merger 
which could take place by the end of year 
at a news conference afterward shevarnadze said we would 
like to build a new europe without military confrontation 
but secretary of state james a baker iii told reporters the 
plan would leave berlin which is expected to become germanys 
capital again surrounded by 380000 soviet troops 
as for all of germany shevardnadze proposed a 50 percent 
reduction in foreign forces over five years from east and west 
germany and then over an unspecified period removing all of them 
except token contingents 
over a fiveyear transitional period shevardnadze said east 
and west germany would be obliged to maintain all concluded 
international treaties and agreements now in effect 
western diplomats interpreted this statement as a soviet attempt 
to delay nato membership for the merged germany 
however shevardnadze went on to say that afterward the 
united germany within its rights can conclude international 
agreements unhindered by other considerations he thereby gave 
approval to the germans right to join any alliance after the 
fiveyear period 
baker replied why not let the sovereign unified germany make 
that decision 
he said the withdrawal of foreign forces should not be imposed 
on the germans in the final settlement to be worked out by the 
allies the united states britain france and soviet union and 
the east german and west german foreign ministers 
the question of a united germanys military stance is the 
biggest obstacle to that agreement the united states wants the new 
country to be a member of the western alliance nato the soviet 
union opposes nato membership for germany 
currently west germany is in nato and east germany is a member 
of the sovietled warsaw pact 
shevardnadzes plan would have the effect of delaying full 
sovereignty for a united germany since during the fiveyear 
transition period it could not declare itself a member of nato 
a us official speaking on condition of anonymity said us 
officials objected to the fiveyear time limit before germany could 
join nato the official said the other western ministers expressed 
the same reservations 
a senior west german official speaking on condition of 
anonymity told reporters his government was opposed to a 
transition period but that there might be room for a windingdown 
process 
a senior british offical also speaking on condition of 
anonymity said that everyone rejected the idea of a transition 
period 
the british official said that a united germany must have full 
sovereignity and not be subject to discriminatory treatment 
despite the disagrement shevardnadze said he expected the 
allies would reach agreement on german unification by the end of 
this year the two german nations already are planning joint 
elections for december 
on another difficult issue the ministers agreed to meet in 
paris on july 17 to consider polands concern about its border with 
germany poland is concerned that lands ceded to it from germany 
after world war ii may be lost to reunification 
shevardnadze said his proposal regarding troops on german soil 
was an outline on which the kremlin was prepared to compromise it 
also contained the following provisions 
1 the united germany must not produce possess receive or 
deploy nuclear chemical or biological weapons 
2 the four power occupation of berlin that has existed since 
world war ii would end within six months of the formation of a 
single german government 
3 the final settlement being drafted by the six nations should 
propose measures to limit the size of germanys armed forces 
4 nato and the warsaw pact would agree on a new code of conduct 
toward each other in which the two alliances no longer would be 
potential military adversaries 
