for a separate tamil homeland the rebels contend tamils are 
discriminated against by the sinhalese majority 
but an associated press reporter who visited the area on 
thursday and friday found the rebels appeared to control large 
parts of the region the coastal town of batticaloa which the 
government claimed to have captured was virtually deserted 
in batticaloa the threestory police station gutted by a fire 
set by tamil rebels was empty and shops were boarded up several 
people roamed the streets searching for food which residents say 
is running short after nearly two weeks of fighting 
government troops only controlled an airstrip on batticaloas 
outskirts on the roads rebels could be seen driving tractor 
trailers loaded with looted food soap and other essentials 
a 25yearold rebel leader who identified himself only as 
newton said the tigers had withdrawn from most of the major towns 
in the east and were readying for guerrilla war 
from now on there will be no negotiations we will ambush and 
attack government troops he said cocking his new chinesemade 
automatic rifle as he spoke to reporters in pullamalia a village 
near batticaloa 
eight miles away sinhalese police peered warily from their 
bunkers in maha oya no one was allowed in or out of the town 
without police permission 
tamil rebels took reporters on a tour of the east coast region 
in an effort to show they were still in control 
at periyaparativu a village 12 miles south of batticaloa most 
of the 300 homes were gutted rebels and some villagers claimed the 
homes had been destroyed by government troops before they withdrew 
when the army came here last week the people fled when they 
withdrew we returned said a 26yearold tamil university 
student 
the tamil tigers have been waging a sevenyear insurgency to set 
up a separate state in the north and east where tamils predominate 
the fighting flared again on june 11 when the rebels abrogated a 
13monthold ceasefire by attacking police stations after a tamil 
civilian complained he was manhandled by sinhalese police 
tamils who are predominantly hindu make up 18 percent of sri 
lankas 16 million people the buddhist sinhalese comprise 75 
