<TEXT>
for the 20 months after her aids diagnosis 
kathy and chris pitkin made the most of the life she had left by 
caring for her at home she lived well with aids instead of simply 
dying well with it 
the 20 months of care before her death in 1988 cost 150000 80 
percent of it for six hospital visits the cost of home care which 
helped extend and improve her life had to come out of pitkins 
pocket 
its one of the most frustrating things we face said merle 
sande chief of medicine at san francisco general hospital during 
a panel discussion friday in connection with the sixth 
international conference on aids 
we can get resources if you hospitalize a patient but to take 
care of them at home to focus on the quality of life to try to 
keep them out of the hospital you cant get support for it it 
doesnt make any sense 
as aids enters its second decade caregivers community aids 
groups and people infected with the deadly virus are talking about 
quality of life home care good nutrition and critical emotional 
support and how it can help lengthen life and give them a sense 
of control over a disease that often seems out of control 
its easier to see whats needed in the bigger picture than it 
is to find money to pay for it 
finding the resources to support it is almost harder to do 
than finding the resources to support what it takes to die well 
said jean mcguire executive director of the aids action council a 
washington dcbased lobbying group 
the council recently challenged the continuing reviews of social 
security and medicaid benefits of people with aids ironically 
current drug therapies were often improving the health of aids 
patients so dramatically that they were deemed no longer eligible 
for the benefits that had given them access the very medical care 
that had helped them she said 
kathleen squires was an intern at a philadelphia hospital in 
1981 when patients started popping up with an illness no one could 
identify 
by the time these patients presented at the hospital they 
never made it out of the hospital again said squires now 
assistant attending physician at new york hospital they were 
subjected to every test known to man and every kind of medication 
and in terms of quality of life there was none 
in many cases there still is none doctors have to begin 
incorporating those concerns into their mainstream care 
psychiatrist stuart nichols said 
we have to go beyond what doctors can do for patients we can 
help patients live longer and function better but quality of life 
ultimately depends on having the courage to look at your life and 
see if youre doing enough with it doing the kind of things you 
want said nichols of beth israel hospital in new york 
physicians tend to focus too narrowly on the negative aspects of 
aids he said 
if you ask most doctors about the basic psychological response 
to being diagnosed theyd tell you about the catastrophic reaction 
where your sense of who you are and where youre going is wiped 
out he said but they seem to forget entirely theres a 
second and more important phase where the patient emerges with 
a new sense of who they are a new sense of what they want to do 
with new friends new goals in life 
pitkin who learned he was hiv positive six years ago has all 
but abandoned the conservative lifestyle that found him pursuing an 
advanced business degree and socking away retirement money 
attitude is everything he believes 
thats the thing with aids its like death and dying and 
everythings going to hell he said lets get out and play 
some golf do some sailing and have some fun 
