<TEXT>
three women convicted of crimes against the 
state are put in an underground prison 
theyre stripsearched daily isolated from other inmates and 
kept under 24hour surveillance by guards and video cameras even 
in the shower everything they do including their conversations 
is logged by their jailers 
this isnt the gulag but a federal prison and it isnt 
fiction but a documentary film through the wire airing 
tuesday night to open the third season of pov the 
independent filmmakers series on pbs 
through the wire is typical of the kinds of risktaking 
unconventional documentaries offered in the 12week run of 
pov the cinematic abbreviation for point of view 
the film examines the high security unit of the federal prison 
at lexington ky which was condemned as a sensory deprivation 
tank for us political prisoners almost from the day it opened in 
1986 
the womens cells get virtually no natural light or ventilation 
their visiting rights correspondence and reading matter are 
severely limited they are barred from training rehabilitation or 
recreation programs 
psychologists call the technique small group isolation it 
makes prisoners easier to manage it is scary to think about it 
being used against people convicted of politically motivated crimes 
next weeks pov is just as unconventional 
metamorphosis man into woman follows two years in the life of 
gary a man who suffers from gender dysphoria the conviction 
that he is a woman trapped in a mans body 
metamorphosis follows gary as he undergoes preliminary 
plastic surgery therapy and other subtler processes he must go 
through to live as a woman and qualify for sex reassignment 
surgery 
its a subdued and sympathetic portrait of a person braving a 
profound transformation its engrossing to watch gary and his 
friends and coworkers cope with his struggle to become gaby 
in through the wire us bureau of prisons officials 
contend the highsecurity unit is not to punish or brainwash the 
women but because they may be subject to rescue attempts by 
outside groups 
the women are 
susan rosenberg indicted in the 1983 bombing of the us 
capitol serving 58 years for possession of weapons and explosives 
with recommendation against parole 
alejandrina torres of the faln puerto rican independence 
movement serving 35 years for seditious conspiracy to bomb a us 
military installation with recommendation against parole 
sylvia baraldini serving 43 years for conspiracy and 
racketeering in aiding and abetting the bloody 1981 brinks armored 
car robbery in nyack ny 
through the wire produced directed and cowritten by nina 
rosenblum has weaknesses including the assertion that the womens 
crimes were nonviolent when in fact they conspired in or 
furthered very violent acts indeed 
theres also a jarringly unnecessary simulation of male 
guards at surveillance monitors watching one woman pacing back and 
forth and another women showering with her back to the camera we 
got the idea without it 
and there are montages of home movies and still photos showing 
the women in their childhoods and preradical days it suggests the 
obvious that even cute welladjusted kids from nice families can 
become dedicated revolutionaries 
and the film finds no irony in its portrayal of revolutionaries 
who attack a government they view as fundamentally evil break its 
laws and then complain that the state isnt playing by the rules 
in the way it punishes them 
even so it becomes obvious in the course of the film that these 
women are suffering in a punishing oppressive environment 
rosenberg especially seems to decline physically and emotionally 
none of them flourishes 
eventually the women sue the bureau of prisons in july 1988 
us district judge barrington parker orders that rosenberg and 
baraldini be moved in with other inmates he forbids the 
consideration of past political associations or personal 
political beliefs in deciding inmate transfers 
he does not find that the units conditions unconstitutionally 
cruel but says the prisoners treatment skirted elemental 
standards of human decency 
through the wire concludes with a few ominous notes 
parkers ruling subsequently was overruled by an appeals court 
the lexington unit was closed but the bureau of prisons opened 
a new highsecurity prison in marianna fla in september 1988 
and there are 16 prisons with similar highsecurity units 
currently under construction or in planning in the united states 
</TEXT>
