<TEXT>
using a farm machine like a giant 
mixing spoon don wilkinson whips up a batch of sewage sludge 
sawdust and papermill waste carefully protecting his recipe for 
garden feed and fill 
its hard to get the formula so we dont let it out 
wilkinson said after climbing down a monstrous device that has 
just chewed up a 100yardlong pile of the reeking black 
concoction 
wilkinson is chief operator at the hawk ridge compost facility 
which turns organic waste into products sold to contractors and 
nurseries 
its also hoping to turn a profit before long after only six 
months the facility already is paying its costs and looking 
forward to making money on its landscaping and garden supplements 
which are made with industrial and municipal sludges long dismissed 
as useless 
all were doing is speeding up natures own work said jamie 
ecker acting manager of hawk ridge 
but the facility is a pioneer in what is widely seen as an 
industry of the future not only does it recycle materials that 
would otherwise be dumped in landfills but it provides evidence 
that caring for the environment doesnt always have to cost money 
the market for these kinds of recycled materials will take off 
and enhance our ability to make money on the venture said 
william ginn president of the yarmouthbased resource conservation 
services inc which owns hawk ridge and is involved in a variety 
of recycling enterprises 
we think composting is going to be one of the major 
solidwaste solutions ginn said 
each week hawk ridge accepts 25 dumptruck loads of dried sewage 
sludge from nearly a dozen communities along with six tractor 
trailers of sawdust and 10 dumptruck loads of papermill waste 
hawk ridge is paid to take the sludge and mill waste but it 
buys the sawdust which is becoming increasingly scarce as more 
paper mills burn it for energy 
wilkinson and his assistant doug knowlton make a new batch of 
compost by taking a base of the old stuff adding papermill 
sludge a layer of sawdust as a bulking agent and sewage sludge 
once the mixture reaches the crucial 131degree temperature 
its turned by steel teeth protruding from huge rollers on a 
customdesigned machine which is driven over the piles every day 
for 15 days 
the heat resulting from biochemical reactions kills 
diseasecausing bacteria in the compost heaps 
while the process seems as simple as spreading manure ecker 
said it took time to develop a mixing and curing formula that 
results in a safe odorless and commercially viable product using 
readily available wastes 
the process is even tracked by computer to make sure each batch 
of compost is made according to recipe said wilkinson 
nora goldstein executive editor of biocycle magazine a journal 
of waste recycling said she knows of no other facility that 
accepts such a wide assortment of wastes for composting 
she also said it is one of few that is privately owned a number 
of municipalities have their own sludge facilities and yardwaste 
sites 
since it opened in march hawk ridge has turned out 6000 cubic 
yards of composted material ecker said its commercial mix is used 
for such projects as landfill closings and highway and industrial 
park landscaping 
a homeowners mix as ecker calls it is made without 
papermill sludge which may contain tiny amounts of dioxin that 
ensures it is completely safe for gardens 
ecker said the company is still in the startup phase were 
not expecting to burn up the mortgage right away he said 
after all no one has done this before on this kind of scale 
but the possibilities appear endless hawk ridge will be 
processing food and paper wastes from fast food restaurants in new 
hampshire in july to see if composting is cheaper for them than 
other means of disposal ecker said 
the facility is composting food wastes from a maine processor 
and may run trials of old supermarket produce 
and an experiment mixing paper plates with sewage sludge was a 
huge success said wilkinson it degraded nice 
