<TEXT>
japans stubbornly high trade surplus with the 
united states is the result of natural factors not closed 
markets the trade ministry said in its annual report today 
the ministry said japan benefits by emphasizing exports of high 
value manufactured goods while the united states relies more on the 
sale of minerals and agricultural commodities 
the ministry of international trade and industrys 1989 white 
paper on trade and the economy also said statistics show japans 
mammoth overall trade surplus will continue to fall despite the 
yens relative weakness against other currencies 
the report was released as japan and the united states were 
preparing to meet june 25 for a final round of trade talks on 
economic reforms aimed at changing business practices and policies 
that inhibit trade and investment 
it said difficulties in slashing japans 49 billion trade 
surplus with the united states could be explained naturally 
a gradual recovery in us export competitiveness boosted us 
exports to japan 659 percent between 1986 and 1989 while us 
exports to the european community rose 629 percent it said 
but while the united states posted a 15 billion trade surplus 
with the ec last year a significant improvement over its 206 
billion deficit in 1987 it ran a 49 billion deficit with japan 
that was a slight improvement from a record 563 billion gap in 
1987 but still huge compared to 1980s 99 billion deficit 
according to the us commerce department 
the report attributed the slower recovery in the us trade 
balance with japan to the composition of goods traded 
higher value manufactured goods account for 806 percent of us 
exports to europe but only 58 percent of us exports to japan it 
said other exports to japan included grain meat lumber iron ore 
and coal 
the report said 781 percent of japans exports to the united 
states were machinery and transport goods for sustaining and 
expanding us domestic industrial activity in contrast 
european exports included more primary products it said 
japans exports are increasingly hightech products that are 
essential to the production and other economic activities of 
companies in the countries that are importing them the report 
said 
it said there were signs of a stable trend toward continued 
growth in imports and reduced reliance by japanese companies on 
exports despite the yens relative weakness against other major 
currencies 
the ministry said the yens average value fell to 138 to the 
dollar in 1989 from 1282 in 1988 in 1985 when the major 
industrial nations agreed to strengthen the yen to help correct 
trade imbalances the dollar bought 2385 yen 
economists have said a weaker yen which makes japanese products 
cheaper on world markets could abort efforts to curb the trade 
imbalance 
indeed the japanese government earlier this week said the 
countrys economy grew strongly in the three months ended in march 
because of a fresh surge in exports 
the trade ministry said japans total trade surplus in 1989 was 
7692 billion down from 9502 billion in 1988 
imports grew 125 percent to 2108 billion last year for the 
first time ever more than half of those imports 503 percent 
were manufactured goods the report said in 1985 only 31 percent 
of japans imports were manufactured goods 
we consider the fact that imports rose despite the weak yen 
to signify that import expansion is here to stay said kazukiyo 
higuchi director of mitis international trade research office 
but the ministrys figures also show that exchange rates and 
other factors brought the rate of increase in the value of imports 
down from 183 percent in 1987 and 253 percent in 1988 growth in 
the volume of imports also slowed to 78 percent last year from 
167 percent in 1988 and over 9 percent in 1987 and 1988 
the report said japans exports climbed only 39 percent in 1989 
to 2752 billion down from a 156 percent increase in 1988 
exports were down 22 percent to 667 billion in the first three 
months of this year 
manufacturers in many sectors have begun to wean themselves from 
strong dependence on exports the report said 
automakers rely on exports for 346 percent of their sales down 
from 464 percent in 1985 it said japanese industry as a whole 
gets only 202 percent of sales from exports compared with 255 
percent in 1985 
