<TEXT>
the streets of warsaw show an economic 
revolution in progress six months after the government jolted the 
country with marketoriented reform but the faces of the people 
show the human cost 
polands plunge into capitalism jan 1 was far bolder than any 
program undertaken by neighboring countries also shedding their 
communist past 
some people are obviously thriving new mercedes and volvos with 
polish license plates are a common sight on warsaw streets a few 
luxury boutiques sell dresses and suits for more than the average 
months salary and do not lack for customers 
there has been a general enlivening of commerce 
but there also is the pathetic sight of old people counting out 
a few zlotys to buy one or two rolls and the banners announcing 
the sale of gas guns to counter the crime wave that police experts 
blame on the hard times 
according to government statistics the country has entered a 
deep recession 
polands rocky experience during the first six months of 
switching to a market economy is giving pause to its giant neighbor 
to the east 
soviet officials so far have rejected radical economic reform 
along polish lines apparently admitting they do not have the 
political credibility to survive such a rapid transition 
instead soviet premier nikolai ryzhkov proposed in late may a 
regulated market economy that called for bread prices to triple 
july 1 and other prices to double jan 1 
panic buying and popular discontent forced postponement of the 
bread price increases 
such halfmeasures typified poland during the 1980s until 
solidarity came to power and its economists declared it was 
impossible to leap a wide chasm in short steps 
bolstered by strong popular support the solidarityled 
government of prime minister tadeusz mazowiecki instituted a plan 
that instantly liberated most prices after decades of control but 
kept wages tied down 
state subsidies for enterprises were ended the easy flow of 
bank credits were staunched by high interest rates the 
deficitridden state budget was balanced 
the polish zloty was made fully convertible inside poland 
backed by a 1 billion reserve fund lent by western nations that 
eliminated the confusing array of legal semilegal and illegal 
exchange rates 
after nearly six months the plans architect finance minister 
leszek balcerowicz can claim a certain success said polish 
economics journalist krzystof bien in an interview 
what he has managed to do so far has never been accomplished 
before he said 
however it is not yet the stage that would permit us to say 
that we are irrevocably on the road to a market economy everything 
we have achieved so far could be destroyed in a day bien said 
the chief potential danger he said is a resurgence of 
inflation if the government relaxes its strict pay policies in 
response to recent industrial strikes and protests by small private 
farmers 
taming runaway inflation estimated at more than 1000 percent 
in 1989 has been the greatest achievement of the program so far 
prices spiked up when the plan was launched but the tight controls 
on wages and lending soon brought them down 
statistics tell the story prices grew 79 percent in january 24 
percent in february 47 percent in march 81 percent in april and 
5 percent in may 
freeing prices while holding down wages had an immediate effect 
on supplies in stores suddenly the chronic shortages evaporated 
because of the drop in demand caused by the high pricetags then as 
supplies become more reliable consumers stopped hoarding further 
helping keep the shelves stocked 
for consumers with money poland has become if not yet a 
shoppers paradise at least a country where one can find most of 
lifes essentials and a few luxuries without irritating lines or 
complicated barters bribes and deals 
sellers are chasing buyers and not the other way around as 
before former luxuries such as bananas and lemons are now sold on 
the street and food stands that have sprung up serve customers at 
night on weekends and on holidays warsaw even has a 24hour 
french grocery 
on the down side unemployment is about 400000 people or about 
3 percent of the work force joblessness officially nonexistent a 
year ago is expected to grow to 9 percent or 13 million people 
this year 
faced with high interest rates and reduced demand many 
factories slowed production to a trickle output by government 
industry is down about 30 percent the dire picture is probably 
offset somewhat by increased production in the private sector where 
government statistics are less reliable 
with wages tied down by punitive taxes and prices steadily 
rising especially in january and february real incomes dropped 
dramatically down about 40 percent according to official 
statistics but again the numbers do not fully reflect the 
burgeoning private business activity 
i am an optimist said slawomir rudnicki the proud coowner 
of the new french grocery it would have been impossible to open 
this shop a few years ago 
but in the next breath he goes on to present a long list of 
complaints against petty officials and regulations that still 
hinder business like the rule that the bottled mineral water he 
imports be submitted to a health check each time his truck crosses 
the polish border 
</TEXT>
