<TEXT>
a federal communications commission order that 
local phone companies reduce their access charges by 11 billion 
nationwide is expected to result in a further reduction in 
longdistance rates 
the fcc on thursday ordered the cut in rates charged to 
longdistance companies for access to local phone networks 
effective july 1 longdistance carriers typically pass along to 
their customers savings from such cuts 
american telephone amp telegraph co the nations largest 
longdistance company announced last month it would cut its rates 
by 160 million annually effective july 1 in anticipation of the 
fcc decision this would mean a cut of 25 percent in typical 
evening rates 
other phone companies such as mci communications corp and us 
sprint usually follow suit to remain competitive 
atampt has decided on deeper rate reductions however since it 
had based its cuts on local phone company proposals to the fcc the 
local companies in april had asked to reduce their access charges 
by just 405 million on july 1 
the fcc ordered an additional 696 million cut thursday saying 
the local phone companies had underestimated likely calling demand 
by about 24 percent or 7 billion minutes 
the fcc also based its rate reductions in part on corrections 
of the local phone companies cost estimates 
there will be some further reduction beyond the 160 million 
atampt proposed may 17 atampt spokesman herb linnen said i dont 
know how much buts its good news for residential and small 
business customers 
he said atampt probably would announce additional cuts next week 
we expect atampt to file reductions in its rates to reflect 
these further reductions said kelly cameron an official in the 
fccs common carrier division 
cameron said the longdistance price cuts would not necessarily 
be a direct flowthrough of access charge savings 
before july 1989 when atampts earnings were restricted to about 
a 12 percent rate of return on its investment the flowthrough of 
costs generally were nearly automatic 
but atampt now is under a regulatory scheme that controls its 
prices within a prescribed range tied to the rate of inflation not 
its profits 
atampts may proposal for 25 percent evening reductions would 
reduce the price of a 10minute directdialed call to anywhere in 
the united states to 153 or less from 158 sunday through 
friday 5 pm to 11 pm 
atampts prices have dropped more than 40 percent since 1984 
separately thursday atampt began offering corporate phone rates 
that match those of its competitors while undercutting rates atampt 
is allowed to charge under its governmentapproved tariffs 
a fivemonth waiting period for the plan under fcc rules expired 
at midnight wednesday said atampt spokesman andy myers 
under the plan atampt must seek government approval each time it 
signs a contract to offer phone rates to a specific customer that 
match those offered to the customer by competitors and are lower 
than atampt is allowed to offer under its tariffs myers said 
in addition the fcc has an additional 12 to 15 months to 
continue its investigation into the socalled tariff 15 plan and 
could decide to disallow the plan during that period said john 
cimko chief of the fccs tariff division 
so far atampt has filed seven requests involving customers such 
as cbs inc and pepsico to offer competitive rates under tariff 
15 myers said 
the rate plan that went into effect thursday is for resort 
condominiums international inc of indianapolis cimko said the 
plan in effect was a test case for tariff 15 
under fcc rules atampt must gain the commissions approval for 
all rate changes while competitors may change rates at will 
however the fcc has said it will examine whether it should relax 
that requirement 
