<TEXT>
an undercover fbi agent in a wideranging probe 
of corruption at the worlds biggest commodities exchanges was no 
bumpkin a federal prosecutor said today in concluding his case 
against three traders 
randall jannett who posed as a corrupt trader at the chicago 
mercantile exchange was a special special agent who 
accurately recalled how the three men all traders in the swiss 
franc pit cheated their customers assistant us attorney james 
p fleissner told jurors at the us district trial before judge 
ann c williams 
ladies and gentlemen randall jannett was no bumpkin 
fleissner said 
defense attorneys for the defendants robert d mosky danny 
scheck and david zatz argued throughout the sixweek trial that 
jannett was in over his head incompetent at discerning what were 
and were not legitimate trades 
thursday moskys attorney elliot samuels told the 12member 
jury that his client was being unfairly blamed for ambiguous 
trading rules at the commodities exchanges 
federal prosecutors contend mosky was the ringleader of a group 
of traders in the mercs swiss franc futures pit who routinely 
stole money from customers through various illegal trading schemes 
that prevented the customer orders from being executed in the open 
market 
but samuels backed by testimony from a merc official contended 
a key trading rule that mosky allegedly broke is subject to 
interpretation according to the customs and practices of the 
marketplace 
heres the governments game folks lets call the conduct 
fraudulent and lets indict the guy samuels told the jury near 
the end of his twohour closing argument 
if theyre not happy with the damn rules let them go to 
washington and get congress to change it but dont bob put mosky 
in jail because of it samuels said 
congress already is addressing the vagueness of some commodity 
trading rules as part of a periodic examination of the industry 
that has taken on added weight after the chicago corruption probe 
samuels referred specifically to the interpretation of open 
outcry trading the accepted method of commodity futures trading 
in which traders crowd into recessed pits to buy and sell 
contracts for future deliveries of commodities through a 
combination of hand signals and shouted bids and offers 
the federal charges are rooted in the premise that the 
defendants executed customer orders through prearranged or 
offmarket trades instead of through open outcry thus depriving 
the customers of the supposedly superior prices that result from 
competitive trading 
the government contends the defendants used the profits from the 
illegal trades to cover their personal losses from trading errors 
samuels cited the testimony of merc executive vice president 
gerald beyer who indicated during crossexamination that the 
precise definition of a legitimate bid or offer whether a 
wordless hand gesture is sufficient for example depends on the 
customs of each trading pit 
samuels said the government had not proved that mosky had not 
executed customer orders through open outcry samuels suggested 
undercover fbi agent randall jannett merely missed moskys legal 
trades then mistook the ensuing confirmation discussion between 
the traders as illegal offmarket trading 
this is the first trial resulting from an unprecedented 
undercover fbi probe of corruption at the merc and the chicago 
board of trade the worlds two biggest commodity exchanges in 
all 48 people were indicted and 16 already have pleaded guilty 
two other groups of traders face september trials 
mosky scheck and zatz face more than a dozen counts each of 
mail or wire fraud and violations of the commodity exchange act 
each count carries a maximum penalty of five years in prison and a 
150000 fine 
mosky also is charged with racketeering conspiracy for which he 
could be sent to prison for 20 years and be forced to forfeit 
personal assets including exchange membership 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

