<TEXT>
coniston partners one of the most prominent 
takeover strategists of the 1980s said friday it is closing up 
shop in response to the shrinking market for mergers and 
acquisitions 
but the three men who led the investor group arent going out of 
business theyre restructuring their operation to reflect the 
changing times 
were realistic said paul e tierney jr one of the three 
founding partners of coniston were trying to adapt our 
investment policy to what we believe to be the current market 
environment and we think its changed a lot 
in its heyday conistons biggest targets included gillette co 
allegis corp and tw services inc 
coniston said it was disbanding the 700 million investment pool 
it used to fund its takeover bids and proxy fights because of the 
scarcity of financing and suitable target companies most of the 
money will be returned to conistons investors 
the trio will continue its investment in ual corp the 
successor to allegis and its ownership of tw services the food 
service company whose operations include the dennys restaurant 
chain 
tierney and his partners augustus k oliver and keith r 
gollust said they would secure financing for future deals on a 
casebycase basis 
disbanding coniston relieves the partners of their 
responsibilities to investors which have become more difficult to 
fulfill with the changes in the takeover market tierney said 
he noted coniston had a 40 percent rate of return before the 
general partners interests were subtracted a very difficult 
rate of return to achieve and sustain with the way the market is 
going 
the trio plans to continue looking for acquisitions but may 
move into areas such as real estate and foreign companies where 
they have not been heavily invested tierney said in an interview 
they will also look for companies in bankruptcy or financial 
distress that need investors and will be involved in arbitrage 
the practice of selling a security in one market and buying it for 
less in another market to profit from the price difference 
the demise of coniston marks the latest retreat of the 1980s 
corporate raiders following the collapse of the junk bond market 
last fall the failure of the 67 billion buyout of federated 
department stores inc by campeau corp last september slowed 
takeover financing to a crawl and brought the merger boom to an end 
coincidentally another big investor group shamrock holdings 
inc also is shifting away from takeovers toward a different kind 
of venture shamrock which failed in a 1988 hostile bid for 
polaroid corp said it is forming a fund to help bail out 
companies that are faltering under heavy debt loads 
news that coniston was closing came on the same day that philip 
morris cos announced it would acquire the swiss coffee and 
chocolate company jacobs suchard ag in a 38 billion deal but 
theres no irony in that 
the deals being done these days including the suchard 
acquisition tend to be strategic moves by companies looking for 
expansion in a related industry that was not the case with 
takeover strategists or corporate raiders like coniston who 
generally were investors seeking profits on their stock holdings 
tierney oliver and gollust all ivy league graduates formed 
coniston in 1982 as the takeover boom was awakening the 
partnership typically took a large stake in a target firm and 
pressured management to take actions to increase the price of the 
companys stock 
one of its biggest successes came in 1987 at allegis the parent 
of united airlines the hertz car rental company and two hotel 
chains 
armed with a 13 percent stake in the company coniston 
threatened a proxy fight and forced the allegis board to fire 
chairman richard j ferris and shed all its assets except for 
united airlines coniston came away with a 175 million profit 
allegis changed its name to ual corp and the companys 
management eventually found itself again tussling with coniston 
the partnership is currently participating in a 438 billion plan 
by united airlines employees to take ual private 
in 1988 coniston lost a proxy fight for four seats on 
gillettes board the partnership and the company later reached an 
agreement under which gillette bought back 16 million of its 
shares giving coniston a profit at least on paper 
last year after a protracted fight coniston won control of tw 
services 
</TEXT>
