<TEXT>
an arrogant young commodities broker devised 
the perfect scam to skim customer profits a prosecutor said 
friday as the first case in a sweeping probe of the worlds largest 
commodities exchanges went to the jury 
robert mosky 34 facing fraud and racketeering charges 
regularly and illegally circumvented the rules of trade at the 
chicago mercantile exchanges swiss franc futures pit assistant 
us attorney james p fleissner said during closing arguments 
jurors were unable to reach a verdict after deliberating two 
hours friday afternoon they will resume at 1030 am edt monday 
mosky and two other traders in the swiss franc pit danny scheck 
and david zatz were the first to stand trial in a lengthy fbi 
investigation of corruption at the mercantile exchange and the 
chicago board of trade 
in all 48 people have been indicted and 16 already have pleaded 
guilty 
mosky was alleged by prosecutors to be the ringleader of a group 
of traders who routinely stole money from customers by trading 
schemes that prevented customer orders from being executed in the 
open market 
its the perfect scam fleissner told jurors who heard 
testimony in us district judge ann c williams courtroom for 
more than six weeks you can do it and you cant get caught 
mosky scheck and zatz were charged last august with more than a 
dozen counts each of mail or wire fraud and violations of the 
commodity exchange act each count carries a maximum penalty of 
five years in prison and a 150000 fine 
mosky also was charged with racketeering conspiracy which 
carries a maximum prison term of 20 years he also could be forced 
to forfeit personal assets 
the government alleged that the three men executed customer 
orders through prearranged or offmarket trades instead of through 
open outcry 
by doing so prosecutors said customers were denied the 
superior prices that would result from open competitive trading 
the defendants were accused of shifting their personal losses 
from trading errors into their customers accounts then hiding 
their practices by changing or destroying trading records 
during closing arguments fleissner argued mosky was arrogant 
and greedy 
once the undercover probe of the exchanges was revealed in 
january 1989 fleissner said mosky told a colleague prosecution 
tape recordings were probably worthless and bragged if no one 
talks theyve got no tapes 
but in closing arguments thursday moskys attorney elliot 
samuels said his client had been scapegoated by overeager 
prosecutors trying to enforce ambiguous commodities trading rules 
if theyre not happy with the damn rules let them go to 
washington and get congress to change it but dont put bob mosky 
in jail because of it samuels said 
his concluding remarks differed considerably from those made by 
the attorneys of scheck and zatz who instead attacked the 
credibility of government witnesses including that of fbi agent 
randall jannett who posed undercover as a corrupt trader 
but fleissner said jannett was no bumpkin 
did agent jannett make mistakes fleissner asked 
rhetorically there were mistakes 
but you go back and count those mistakes up see how far you 
get on your second hand he instructed the jury 
