honeywells autofocus patent infringement lawsuit has been 
pending for more than three years when honeywell announced june 14 
it was asking the itc to ban imports on minolta maxxum cameras and 
other models the company said a trial was two years away 
honeywell said it was calling for the import ban in hopes of 
getting quicker relief the minneapolisbased company said it is 
unjustly losing millions of dollars in royalties while the case is 
being litigated 
the lawsuit accuses minolta of infringing on four honeywell 
patents the itc action sought to ban imports of maxxum cameras and 
others including aftele and freedom dual models 
honeywell contends that minolta breached a 1979 contract calling 
for honeywell to share patented technology and trade secrets 
minolta was restricted to using only honeywellmade autofocus 
modules under the contract honeywell said 
instead honeywell alleges minolta used honeywell autofocus 
technology while developing a module of its own 
minolta said honeywells patent claims are invalid and 
unenforceable the japanese company said its own autofocus 
innovation dates to the 1960s and is well documented by many us 
patents 
the suit seeks unspecified damages and a sales injunction 
honeywells filing with the itc was in clear violation of a 
prior court order minolta spokesman michael gross said their 
withdrawal was solely to avoid the consequences of this violation 
gross said a court hearing had been set for monday in us 
district court in newark nj to challenge the itc filing he 
said honeywell ran the risk of being formally ordered by the 
court to withdraw 
christopher j steffen honeywell vice president and chief 
financial officer said the company was dropping its itc action 
because it was very pleased that our case has been accelerated by 
more than one year 
the fixed trial date will end minoltas continued efforts to 
delay the court case and will produce a decision in the same time 
frame as the itc action steffen said 
but gross said it was honeywells legal maneuvering that 
prompted delays in the case he said the september trial date came 
as no surprise to minolta 
were very happy with the trial date gross said we 
welcome honeywells decision to drop its itc complaint and abide by 
its 1988 agreement to adjudicate this case in the federal court 
</TEXT>
